.TH PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Version 1.0" "Custom Library Functions"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion with style and grace
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <stdio.h>
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.br
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B _printf()
is the most magnificent formatted output function you have ever encountered!
Created by the legendary programming duo
.I Aljawharah
and
.I Manar
from Saudi Cohort 4 at Tuwaiq Academy, this function brings the power of printf
to new heights of elegance and efficiency.
.PP
The function writes output to the standard output stream according to the
.I format
string and any additional arguments. It is like having a personal assistant
that formats your output perfectly every single time!
.PP
Supported format specifiers include the most popular ones from the standard
.B printf()
family, plus some extra magic:
.TP 12
.B %s
The string whisperer! Converts and displays strings with grace.
.TP
.B %c
The character maestro! Prints individual characters beautifully.
.TP
.B %d %i
The number ninjas! Handle signed integers like pros.
.TP
.B %u
The unsigned champion! Works with non-negative integers.
.TP
.B %o
The octal oracle! Displays numbers in base-8 glory.
.TP
.B %x %X
The hexadecimal heroes! Lowercase and uppercase hex formatting.
.TP
.B %b
The binary boss! Shows numbers in pure binary form.
.TP
.B %%
The percent perfectionist! Displays a literal % character.
.PP
.B Buffer Magic:
This implementation uses a 1024-character buffer for maximum performance,
reducing system calls and making your output lightning fast!
.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful completion,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters written (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).
.PP
If an output error is encountered, a negative value is returned.
.PP
Think of it as your personal output counter, always keeping track! üìä
.SH FORMAT SPECIFIERS EXPLAINED
.SS String Formatting (%s)
.PP
The most versatile specifier! Handles string inputs with elegance:
.PP
.RS
.B _printf("Hello %s!", "World");
.RE
.PP
Output:
.PP
.RS
Hello World!
.RE
.PP
Null pointers are handled gracefully by displaying "(null)".
.SS Character Display (%c)
.PP
Perfect for printing individual characters:
